      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked so that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance between them. It is fundamentally different from classical correlation because classical correlations arise from pre-existing properties (like two gloves in separate boxes), whereas entangled particles do not have definite states until measured. In quantum mechanics, measuring one particle immediately determines the state of its partner, a connection that Einstein famously called \"spooky action at a distance.\"\n\nTo put it simply, if you have two entangled particles, measuring the spin of one as \"up\" will instantly cause the other to be \"down,\" even if they are light-years apart. This is not just a statistical coincidence; the particles share a single quantum state that cannot be described independently. This non-local connection defies our classical intuition about how objects in the universe should behave.\n\nHere is a quick summary of the key differences:\n\n*   **Pre-determined vs. Indeterminate:** In classical correlation, objects have definite properties before measurement (e.g., a coin is either heads or tails before you look). In entanglement, the properties are undefined until a measurement occurs.\n*   **Independence:** Classical",
      "source": "target",
