      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so when you say it's \"spooky\" and doesn't follow classical rules, is there like a specific reason why it feels so weird to physicists? like is there a concept for why those particles stay connected even when they're far apart?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That \"spookiness\" comes from the violation of **local realism**, which is the idea that objects only interact with their immediate surroundings (locality) and have definite properties independent of observation (realism). Physicists are weirded out because, in our everyday world, if you send a ball to the moon, you can't instantly change its spin just by touching it here on Earth; the speed of light acts as a cosmic speed limit for information.\n\nHowever, entangled particles seem to bypass this limit. The connection isn't a physical tether like a string; it's more like a shared existence where the particles are fundamentally one system, not two separate ones. Even when separated by vast distances, they remain entangled because they were created together or interacted closely before, and the universe seems to treat them as a single entity despite the space in between.\n\nIt's like two coins that, no matter how far apart they are, always land on opposite sides the moment you flip them. In classical physics, you'd say one coin was already heads and the other tails before you flipped them (hidden variables). But in quantum mechanics, they genuinely don't have a state until the moment of measurement, and the act of measuring one",
      "source": "target",
